</subtitle><entry><title type="html">2018 Predictions</title><link href="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/2018-predictions" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="2018 Predictions" /><published>2018-01-16T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2018-01-16T23:31:54-05:00</updated><id>https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/2018-predictions</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/2018-predictions">&lt;h2 id=&quot;the-end-of-crowdsourcing&quot;&gt;The End of Crowdsourcing&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With Russian bots on Twitter,
&lt;a href=&quot;https://qz.com/1160551/the-rotten-tomatoes-score-for-the-last-jedi-may-be-rigged/&quot;&gt;the attack on Rotten Tomatoes scores&lt;/a&gt;,
&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-internet-pew/over-half-of-public-comments-to-fcc-on-net-neutrality-appear-fake-study-idUSKBN1DT297&quot;&gt;the deluge of fake comments sent to the FCC&lt;/a&gt;,
&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.wired.com/2015/02/how-a-lone-hacker-shredded-the-myth-of-crowdsourcing/&quot;&gt;and even attacks on a DARPA Network Challenge&lt;/a&gt;, I think 2018
is the beginning of the end for crowdsourcing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are two problems to solve, the first is that some of these systems
are trying to extract a signal from noisy data, and it only takes a small
number of bad actors to intentionally inject a strong signal into that data
stream.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The second problem is simply identity on the web. It’s 2018 and it’s still
true that &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_the_Internet,_nobody_knows_you%27re_a_dog&quot;&gt;on the Internet, nobody knows you’re a dog&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Joe Gregorio</name></author><summary type="html">The End of Crowdsourcing</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Another addition to the IndieWeb</title><link href="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/another-addition-to-the-indieweb" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Another addition to the IndieWeb" /><published>2018-01-15T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2018-01-16T23:08:04-05:00</updated><id>https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/another-addition-to-the-indieweb</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/another-addition-to-the-indieweb">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://singletary.io/2018/so-indieweb-giving-this-a-try-thanks-to-indirect-suggestions&quot;&gt;Michael Singletary&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Hoping this post, syndication, and backfeeding works as expected!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Welcome!&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Joe Gregorio</name></author><summary type="html">Michael Singletary</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Going beyond minimal Webmentions</title><link href="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/going-beyond-minimal-webmentions" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Going beyond minimal Webmentions" /><published>2018-01-14T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2018-01-15T00:03:24-05:00</updated><id>https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/going-beyond-minimal-webmentions</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/going-beyond-minimal-webmentions">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://stream.boffosocko.com/2018/i-suspect-that-next-with-a-tad-bit-of-parsing&quot;&gt;Chris Aldrich&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;I suspect that next, with a tad bit of parsing using microformats, you can
add some display elements to your webmentions to indicate the author, their
url, date/time, and actually include the reply text to have a better UI for
them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Indeed, my current implementation just shows the validated Webmention
links, and my plan is to slowly enhance them over time. I think, just like
in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://willnorris.com/go/webmention&quot;&gt;case of the basic Webmention support&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://willnorris.com&quot;&gt;Will
Norris&lt;/a&gt; may have my back again and have already done
the heavy lifting for &lt;a href=&quot;https://willnorris.com/go/microformats&quot;&gt;Microformats and Go&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Joe Gregorio</name></author><summary type="html">Chris Aldrich</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">First</title><link href="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/first" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="First" /><published>2018-01-14T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2018-01-14T10:20:18-05:00</updated><id>https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/first</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/first">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://stream.boffosocko.com/2018/if-youve-got-incoming-webmentions-working-let-me-have-the&quot;&gt;Chris Aldrich&lt;/a&gt; has the honor of being
the first sender of an organic incoming Webmention received on
&lt;a href=&quot;https://bitworking.org&quot;&gt;bitworking.org&lt;/a&gt;, which you can see on &lt;a href=&quot;https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/comments&quot;&gt;this post&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I say “organic” because I’ve been using all the &lt;a href=&quot;https://indieweb.org/Webmention-developer#How_to_test&quot;&gt;testing tools listed on the indieweb.org site&lt;/a&gt;
to test my implementation.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Joe Gregorio</name></author><summary type="html">Chris Aldrich has the honor of being the first sender of an organic incoming Webmention received on bitworking.org, which you can see on this post.</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">WebMention Only</title><link href="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/webmention-only" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="WebMention Only" /><published>2018-01-13T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2018-01-13T17:13:33-05:00</updated><id>https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/webmention-only</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://bitworking.org/news/2018/01/webmention-only">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://allinthehead.com/retro/378/implementing-webmentions&quot;&gt;Drew McLellan has gone WebMention-only.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

